It is based on a set of axioms that describe the properties of points, lines, and planes in a two- or three-dimensional space. Euclidean geometry is also known as "plane geometry" or "elementary geometry."

Riemannian geometry, on the other hand, is a more general type of geometry that deals with spaces of arbitrary dimensions. It is named after Bernhard Riemann, a German mathematician who developed the theory in the 19th century. Riemannian geometry is based on a different set of axioms than Euclidean geometry and it has many more structures attached to it, such as metrics, connections, and curvatures.

One of the main differences between Euclidean geometry and Riemannian geometry is the structure of their geometries. In Euclidean geometry, the parallel postulate is used to define the concept of "parallel lines," while in Riemannian geometry, the concept of "parallel lines" is defined in terms of "geodesics," which are the shortest path between two points in the space. Additionally, the notions of "angles" and "circles" are different in Riemannian geometry compared to Euclidean geometry.

Riemannian geometry has many applications in physics, especially in general relativity and differential geometry. It is also used in some areas of computer science, such as camera calibration and computer vision.
